We all know the protocols for keeping safe against the coronavirus - social distancing, washing our hands and staying indoors. But as Cape Town reporter Ayesha Ismail finds out, in some cases it’s easier said than done when staying indoors poses more of a health risk than being outside. Courtesy #DStv403 MITCHELLS PLAIN - We all know the protocols around keeping us safe against the coronavirus -- social distancing, washing our hands and staying indoors. But in some cases, it’s easier said than done when staying indoors poses more of a health risk than being outside. Rushana Fataar moved in with her parents 37 years ago and the family continued to grow. WATCH: Social distancing a challenge for family of 32 There are 46 people living in one house and 30 of them are children. They share one bath and one toilet and take turns to sleep in the few beds. They say they’re trying their best to keep safe and to protect themselves from catching the coronavirus.  READ: COVID-19: Mkhize calls for a focus on Western Cape “We have to get up at four in the morning so that each one can get a turn to use the toilet and the children need to be bathed," Fataar said. The local pastor says it’s a miracle that not a single soul in this house has tested positive for COVID-19. He’s asking for help. “Under the corona regulations, it’s for the premier to do an intervention here," said pastor Dean Ramjoomia. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.